y. DA underestimated Minnesota Hub by $894/MWh at the peak while overestimating Louisiana Hub by $712/MWh—a $1,600/MWh swing in forecast error between North and South. For BESS operators, these DA-RT spreads represent additional capture opportunity beyond pure arbitrage. ... The price divergence reflects MISO's unique geography. The North-South constraint is contractual, not physical. ... ​Minnesota's average real-time LMP across the storm reached $206/MWh. Illinois averaged $118/MWh. The 75% gap stems ... cheaper sources of generation while Minnesota sat behind transmission bottlenecks. The divergence matters for BESS siting. A battery in Minnesota would have captured the $1,351/MWh spike. The same asset ... * **Storm capture is real, but location dependent.**Minnesota offered $2,873/MW-day TB4 spreads, while Mississippi offered $678. Same storm, same weekend, 4x difference in returns. ... $2,873. Weatherization and fuel supply contracts since 2021 have reduced extreme spikes. Don't underwrite for Uri. * **Congestion patterns are predictable.**Minnesota's +$31/MWh average congestion versus Illinois's -$42/MWh reflects ... [![ME BESS ERCOT January 2026: Winter Storm Fern comes to Texas]] \n[Revenue Benchmark] \n1 day ago ... [] [Winter Storm Fern drove battery revenues in PJM during January 2026. A 1 MW, 4-hour battery could have earned $35/kW-month. Day-Ahead spreads"
